edisplay.cfm&Country=395 |archive-date=15 June 2006 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 2005\n| align=\"center\" | 144\n|-\n| World Bank<ref>{{cite web|url=http://econ.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/DATASTATISTICS/0,,contentMDK:20394872~menuPK:1192714~pagePK:64133150~piPK:64133175~theSitePK:239419,00.html|publisher=World Bank|title=World Development Indicators|access-date=29 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319051205/http://econ.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/DATASTATISTICS/0,,contentMDK:20394872~menuPK:1192714~pagePK:64133150~piPK:64133175~theSitePK:239419,00.html|archive-date=19 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 2008\n| align=\"center\" | 160\n|-\n| CIA World FactBook<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/bg.html | publisher = CIA | title = CIA World Factbook 2010 }}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 2010\n| align=\"center\" | 156\n|-\n| World Population Reference<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prb.org/Publications/PopulationBulletins/2010/worldpopulationhighlights2010.aspx | publisher = World Population Reference | title = World Population Highlights: Key Findings From PRB's 2010 World Population Data Sheet | access-date = 29 August 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100904063524/http://www.prb.org/Publications/PopulationBulletins/2010/worldpopulationhighlights2010.aspx | archive-date = 4 September 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 2010\n| align=\"center\" | 164\n|}\n\nAccording to the OECD/World Bank population in Bangladesh increased from 1990 to 2008 with 44 million and 38% growth in population compared to 34% growth in [[Demographics of India|India]] and 54% growth in [[Demographics of Pakistan|Pakistan]]. The annual population growth 2007-2008 was 1.4% compared to India 1.35%, Pakistan 2.2%, [[Demographics of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Dem. Rep. of Congo]] 2.9%, [[Demographics of Tanzania|Tanzania]] 2.9%, [[Demographics of Syria|Syria]] 3.5% or [[Demographics of Yemen|Yemen]] 4.0%. According to the OECD/World Bank population statistics between 1990-2008 the [[world population]] [[Population growth|growth]] was 27% and 1,423 million persons.<ref name=IEApop2011>[http://www.iea.org/co2highlights/co2Highlights.XLS CO2 Emissions from Fuel Combustion] Population 1971-2008 ([http://iea.org/co2highlights/co2highlights.pdf pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106205757/http://iea.org/co2highlights/co2highlights.pdf |date=6 January 2012 }} pages 83-85) IEA (OECD/ World Bank) original population ref e.g. in IEA Key World Energy Statistics 2010 page 57</ref>\n\n===Population growth rate===\n[[File:Dhaka 14th March (32624769393).jpg|thumb|right|A view of [[Paltan]] area in [[Dhaka]] in 2017]]\nBangladesh had high rates of population growth in the 1960s and 1970s. Since then however it has seen significant reduction in its total [[fertility rate]]. Over a period of three decades it dropped from almost 7 to 2.4 in 2005-2010.<ref name=\"WPP 2017\"/>\n\n===Gender ratio===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"100pt\"|Age range (years)\n! width=\"100pt\"|Sex ratio (males/females) (2015 est.)<ref name=\"CIA World Factbook 2015\">{{cite web |title=The World Factbook: Bangladesh: People and Society |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/bg.html#People |publisher=Central Intelligence Agency |accessdate=17 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| at birth\n| align=\"right\" | 1.04\n|-\n| 0\u201314\n| align=\"right\" | 1.03\n|-\n| 15\u201324\n| align=\"right\" | 0.89\n|-\n| 25\u201354\n| align=\"right\" | 0.90\n|-\n| 55\u201364\n| align=\"right\" | 1.01\n|-\n| 65 and over\n| align=\"right\" | 0.97\n|-\n| total population\n| align=\"right\" | 0.95\n|}\n\n===Urban and rural===\nThe sprawling mega-city of Dhaka has a huge population, but the majority of the people nonetheless still live in villages in rural areas.\n:Urban population: 27% of total population (2009 est.)\n:Rate of urbanization: 3.5% annual rate of change (2005-2010 est.)\n:Bangladesh is considered an urban country based on their population density (hrsa.gov)\n\n===Population Density===\nBased on the CIA World Fact Book 2012 figures for population (161,083,804) and land area (130,168&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), Bangladesh has the highest population density among large countries, 1,237.51 persons per square kilometre, and 12th overall, when small countries and city-states are included.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.photius.com/rankings/geography/population_density_persons_per_sq_km_2012_0.html |title=Population density \u2013 Persons per sq km 2012 Country Ranks |accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Vital statistics==\n\n===Births and deaths <ref name=\"WPP 2017\" />===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"80pt\"|Period\n! width=\"80pt\"|Live births per year\n! width=\"80pt\"|Deaths per year\n! width=\"80pt\"|Natural change per year\n! width=\"80pt\"|CBR<sup>1</sup>\n! width=\"80pt\"|CDR<sup>1</sup>\n! width=\"80pt\"|NC<sup>1</sup>\n! width=\"80pt\"|TFR<sup>1</sup>\n! width=\"80pt\"|IMR<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n| 1950-1955\n| align=\"right\" | 1 963 000\n| align=\"right\" |  852 000\n| align=\"right\" | 1 111 000\n| align=\"right\" | 48.3\n| align=\"right\" | 20.9\n| align=\"right\" | 27.4\n| align=\"right\" | 6.36\n| align=\"right\" | 165.0\n|-\n| 1955-1960\n| align=\"right\" | 2 252 000\n| align=\"right\" |  921 000\n| align=\"right\" | 1 332 000\n| align=\"right\" | 48.2\n| align=\"right\" | 19.7\n| align=\"right\" | 28.5\n| align=\"right\" | 6.62\n| align=\"right\" | 156.5\n|-\n| 1960-1965\n| align=\"right\" | 2 560 000\n| align=\"right\" |  994 000\n| align=\"right\" | 1 566 000\n| align=\"right\" | 47.5\n| align=\"right\" | 18.4\n| align=\"right\" | 29.1\n| align=\"right\" | 6.80\n| align=\"right\" | 151.2\n|-\n| 1965-1970\n| align=\"right\" | 2 950 000\n| align=\"right\" | 1 090 000\n| align=\"right\" | 1 860 000\n| align=\"right\" | 47.3\n| align=\"right\" | 17.